        adaptedContent: "## Supply Chain Impact Assessment: US-China Tariff Changes\n\n### Which Suppliers Are Hit\n\nAny supplier with China-origin components in these categories:\n- **PCB components and ICs** — 25% → 40% duty. This hits our Shenzhen suppliers directly.\n- **Semiconductor equipment** — new 15% duty. Affects capital equipment purchases from Chinese OEMs.\n- **Rare earth magnets** — 10% → 30%. Motor and sensor components.\n\n### Lead Time Impact\n\nIf we shift sourcing to Vietnam/India alternatives:\n- **Vietnam:** 6-8 week qualification cycle for existing component specs. Lead times 2-3 weeks longer than Shenzhen. Quality comparable for PCB assembly.\n- **India:** 8-12 week qualification. Lead times 3-4 weeks longer. Strong on passive components, weaker on ICs.\n- **Mexico (nearshoring):** 4-6 week qualification. Lead times cut by 50% vs Asia. Limited IC capability but strong for assembly.\n\n### Inventory Strategy\n\n**Immediate (next 30 days):** Build 90-day safety stock on affected components at current rates before suppliers adjust pricing.\n\n**Medium-term (60-90 days):** Qualify top 5 alternative suppliers. Dual-source critical components.\n\n**Long-term:** Shift 40-60% of affected volume to non-China sources by Q4. Don't go 100% — maintain China as backup for surge capacity.\n\n### The Real Risk\n\nIt's not the tariff cost — it's supply chain fragility. Single-source from China + tariff volatility = one policy change away from margin collapse. Diversification isn't optional anymore.",
