        adaptedContent: "## A New Treatment for Depression That Didn't Respond to Anything Else\n\n### What Is This?\n\nResearchers found a new medicine — called AX-7 — that may help people whose depression didn't get better with other medications. About 1 in 3 people with depression fall into this category. That's 47 million Americans.\n\n### Does It Work?\n\nIn the first small study (48 people), **68% of patients felt significantly better within 6 weeks.** These were people who had already tried 3 or more other antidepressants without success. That's a hopeful number — but it's early.\n\n### Is It Safe?\n\nSo far, the side effects have been manageable. A small number of patients showed changes in liver function tests, but these went back to normal. The larger study (340 patients) will give us a much clearer picture of safety.\n\n### What's Different About This Medicine?\n\nMost antidepressants target serotonin — the same system Prozac targets, which was discovered in the 1980s. AX-7 works on a completely different system in the brain. That's why it might help people who didn't respond to the usual medications.\n\n### When Can Patients Access It?\n\nThe next study starts in Q3 2026. If it goes well, the medicine could be available in 3-5 years after FDA review. We know that feels like a long time when you're suffering. But this is moving faster than most drug development.\n\n### How Can Patients Participate?\n\nThe Phase II trial is enrolling 340 patients across 12 hospitals. If you or someone you know has tried 3+ antidepressants without adequate response, you may be eligible.\n\n**The most important thing:** There is hope. Research hasn't given up on the people the current medications can't help.",
